By the way, this initiative appeared before the start of the war and the bill 7176.
So on February 22, this norm was included in the comparative table of the bill 5397.
Overall, the desire to disband the supervisory boards in one way or another has been circulating among some elected officials for a long time.
Not for the sake of criticism as such, but in order to demonstrate the possible consequences of the draft law, let us analyze the arguments that explained the need for its adoption.
And then we will provide our proposals on how to address the issue of managing state-owned enterprises during war.
The first deputy minister of economy, Denis Kudin, explained the necessity of this innovation due to the risks of losing internet and other means of communication, which would make remote work of supervisory boards impossible.
In other words, the risk is that the supervisory board will not be able to make necessary decisions, which could result in the paralysis of the company's operations.
We agree that there is such a risk, but can the relocation of members of supervisory boards to Ukraine prevent it?
Let‚Äôs imagine a rather cynical situation when independent members of the supervisory boards (who make up the majority of the entire composition) prioritize their personal safety over the interests of the company and refuse to come to Ukraine.
In this case, according to the draft law, they can be fired.
And further, most likely, this will lead to the loss of a quorum necessary for the supervisory board to make any decisions.
However, it will not be possible to quickly appoint new independent members of the supervisory board, as the law requires the need for a competitive selection process, which usually takes 3-4 months.
Therefore, the proposed decision by the draft law 7176 will most likely not be able to prevent the board from losing the ability to make decisions, but rather will lead to that outcome!
People's deputy and author of the draft law, Dmytro Natalukha, provides additional arguments to support it.
In particular, he notes: "many enterprises, especially in the defense industry complex (DIC), now require relocation" and therefore "it is difficult to imagine that a person, for example, from Vienna can discuss addresses and other sensitive information via Zoom."
To begin with, in Ukraine there are almost no state-owned companies in the military-industrial complex that have supervisory boards.
The supervisory board exists only in "Ukroboronprom", which essentially manages almost all state-owned enterprises in the defense industry.
But even in "Ukroboronprom", according to the legislation, the supervisory board has quite limited powers, and all its members perform their duties on a non-gratuitous basis.
"All power in Ukroboronprom belongs to the general director, who by the way will make decisions regarding the need to relocate a particular enterprise of the defense industry, which is part of the concern."
Moreover, this argument does not withstand criticism also because the bill 7176 does not make any changes to the legislation regulating the activities of state-owned enterprises in the defense industry.
Mr. Dmytro also cites arguments on his Facebook page that can be classified as "emotional".
Such arguments, as a rule, have nothing to do with improving the efficiency of the work of state-owned companies and state banks, but let's try to consider some of them: "respected foreign experts, at the first mention of "war", still in 2021 leave Ukraine, but at the same time remain members of supervisory boards in Ukrainian state-owned enterprises with a full salary of several hundred thousand hryvnias, while Ukraine itself is really suffering from the war".
Firstly, this is manipulation - the majority of such board members had never lived in Ukraine and only occasionally came here.
To say that they are "leaving Ukraine", to put it mildly, is unfair.
Secondly, as a result of the coronavirus pandemic, both foreign and Ukrainian members of supervisory boards have long resorted to the practice of holding online meetings.
This tool is widely used in global practice, in completely different spheres: business, education, medicine, etc.
It is also worth noting that membership on the supervisory board is not a full-time job.
As a rule, such people have other occupations and electronic means of communication help them with this.
Thirdly, all these statements are read as claims exclusively against foreigners.
It's interesting why Mr. Dmytro doesn't express identical claims towards the members of supervisory boards who are Ukrainians?
Because they are also not located at the location of their companies.
By the way, this is not the first populist attempt by deputies to remove foreigners from supervisory boards, and the war is just a new convenient opportunity.
